Hospital Category Risk Adjustment: STRING¶

  • Acute Care Hospital
  • Long-Term Acute Care Hospital
  • Critical Access Hospital
  • Rehabilitation Hospital

However, for SSI, only the Acute Care Hospitals have risk adjustment models that are also used for Critical Access Hospitals.

NHSN does not calculate an SSI SIR for Rehabilitation Hospitals/Units and LTAC Hospitals, and thus these facility types are not included.

Facility Type: TEXT¶

  • Major Teaching

    • major teaching hospital is a hospital that has a teaching program for medical students and a post-graduate medical training program

  • Pediatric

    • A pediatric hospital is a hospital with inpatients predominantly age 18 years or younger.

  • Community >250 Beds

    • A community hospital is a CDPH designation for hospitals not classified as major teaching, long-term acute care (LTAC), critical access, pediatric, or rehabilitation.
    • Community hospitals are further categorized by the number of active beds as reported by the hospital in the NHSN Annual Survey.

  • Community 125-250 Beds

    • A community hospital is a CDPH designation for hospitals not classified as major teaching, long-term acute care (LTAC), critical access, pediatric, or rehabilitation.
    • Community hospitals are further categorized by the number of active beds as reported by the hospital in the NHSN Annual Survey.

  • Community <125 Beds

    • A community hospital is a CDPH designation for hospitals not classified as major teaching, long-term acute care (LTAC), critical access, pediatric, or rehabilitation.
    • Community hospitals are further categorized by the number of active beds as reported by the hospital in the NHSN Annual Survey.

  • Long-Term Acute Care

    • A LTAC hospital is defined by the Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services (CMS) as a licensed general acute care hospital providing care for patients with medically complex conditions requiring an average length of stay greater than 25 days.

  • Critical Access

    • A critical access hospital is designated by CMS as a hospital with 25 or fewer acute care inpatient beds, located more than 35 miles from another hospital (with some exceptions), with an average length of stay of four days or less.

  • Rehabilitation Unit

    • A rehabilitation unit is an inpatient ward within a general acute care hospital providing evaluation and restoration of function for patients who have lost function due to:
      • Acute or chronic pain,
      • Musculoskeletal problems,
      • Stroke, or catastrophic events,
      • Resulting in complete or partial paralysis.
    • A rehabilitation unit typically has its own unique CMS certification number (CCN) and reports separately from the rest of the hospital.

  • Rehabilitation Hospital:

    • An acute care facility exclusively providing evaluation and restoration of function for patients who have lost function due to
      • Acute or chronic pain,
      • Musculoskeletal problems,
      • Stroke, or catastrophic events,
      • Resulting in complete or partial paralysis.

NHSN does not calculate an SSI SIR for rehabilitation hospitals/units and LTAC hospitals, and thus these facility types are not included.

The Standardized Infection Ratio (SIR): DECIMAL¶

  • The Standardized Infection Ratio (SIR) is a summary measure used to track Surgical Site Infections (SSIs) over time.

  • It is calculated by dividing the number of observed infections by the number of predicted infections.

  • The SIRs in this table were calculated using only complex SSIs identified during:

    • Hospital Admission, or
    • Readmission to the same hospital following in-patient surgeries.

  • The SIR adjusts for patient-level and hospital-level risk factors specific to each procedure type.

  • NHSN (National Healthcare Safety Network) calculates an SSI SIR when at least one infection is predicted.

  • The California Department of Public Health (CDPH) calculates an SIR if the predicted number of SSIs was <1 and >=0.2.

  • The SIR and its comparison are not as precise as SIRs based on a larger number of predicted infections but provide more hospitals with a published interpretation of their data.

NOTE: See NHSN's Guide to the SIR at the NHSN website for more information.

In [32]:
df = df[(df['infections_predicted'] >=0.2) & ( df['infections_predicted'] < 1)]
In [33]:
df['sir'] =  df['infections_reported'] / df['infections_predicted']

The 2015 Standardized Infection Ratio (SIR): NUMERIC¶

  • The 2015 Standardized Infection Ratio (SIR) is a summary measure used to track Healthcare-Associated Infections (HAIs) over time.

  • The SIR compares the number of reported Surgical Site Infections (SSI) to the number of predicted SSIs based on national baseline data.

  • The SIR adjusts for factors that may impact the risk of acquiring an SSI.

  • Calculated SIR if the number of predicted infections were >=0.2 and <1

  • Hospitals with a predicted number of SSIs equal to or less than 0.2 will not have an SIR calculated by NHSN (National Healthcare Safety Network) or CDPH (California Department of Public Health).

SIR_CI_95_Lower_Limit: NUMERIC¶

  • The lower limit of the SIR 95% confidence interval is computed using the exact Poisson distribution.

  • The confidence interval quantifies the precision of the calculated SIR that is associated with random variation.

Comparison: TEXT¶

  • This field shows if the 95% confidence interval indicates the SSI incidence is significantly:

    • Better,
    • Worse, or
    • The same as predicted.

  • If the 95% confidence interval for the SIR includes 1, the number of reported cases is not statistically significantly different from that predicted.

Met_2020_Goal: TEXT¶

  • "Yes" indicates the hospital met the 2020 national Healthcare-Associated Infections (HAI) reduction goal, as recommended by the CDPH HAI Advisory Committee, in the calendar year of 2022.

  • Starting from 2015, hospitals should have achieved a 30% reduction in Surgical Site Infection (SSI) incidence (SIR < 0.70) to meet the goal.

  • Skewness: A measure of the asymmetry of the probability distribution. A value closer to zero indicates a more symmetrical distribution. Positive skew indicates a tail on the right side, while negative skew indicates a tail on the left.

  • Kurtosis: A measure of whether the data is heavy-tailed or light-tailed compared to a normal distribution. Higher kurtosis means more of the variance is due to infrequent extreme deviations.

Data Transformation¶

  • square root normalizations have been applied on procedure_count and infection_reported

  • Log normalizations have been applied on infections_predicted, sir, sir_ci_95_low and sir_ci_95_high

In [50]:
import numpy as np

transformed_data = df.copy()

transformed_data['procedure_count_sqrt'] = np.sqrt(transformed_data['procedure_count'])
transformed_data['infections_reported_sqrt'] = np.sqrt(transformed_data['infections_reported'])

transformed_data['infections_predicted_log'] = np.log1p(transformed_data['infections_predicted'])
transformed_data['sir_log'] = np.log1p(transformed_data['sir'])
transformed_data['sir_ci_95_lower_limit_log'] = np.log1p(transformed_data['sir_ci_95_lower_limit'])
transformed_data['sir_ci_95_upper_limit_log'] = np.log1p(transformed_data['sir_ci_95_upper_limit'])

Validating the Central Limit Theorem (CLT) with the SIR for Gastric Surgeries¶

Statistical Concept: Central Limit Theorem (CLT) Method: Analysis of sample means distributions for different sample sizes

Analysis:

The standard deviation of the sample means decreases as the sample size increases. This is consistent with the Central Limit Theorem, which states that as the sample size increases, the sampling distribution of the mean will become increasingly normal, regardless of the population's distribution.

In [80]:
gastric_surgery_sir = df[df['operative_procedure'] == 'gastric surgery']['sir'].dropna()

sample_sizes = [10, 30, 50, 100]
sample_means = {n: [np.mean(np.random.choice(gastric_surgery_sir, n, replace=False)) for _ in range(1000)] for n in sample_sizes}

sample_means_distributions = {n: np.std(mean_list) for n, mean_list in sample_means.items()}

sample_means_distributions
Out[80]:
{10: 0.6319537140920765,
 30: 0.3290946506436524,
 50: 0.21233042143718844,
 100: 0.07110537132931088}
In [81]:
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))

for n, means in sample_means.items():
    sns.kdeplot(means, label=f'Sample Size {n}')

plt.title('Distribution of Sample Means for Different Sample Sizes (Gastric Surgery SIR)')
plt.xlabel('Sample Mean of SIR')
plt.ylabel('Density')
plt.legend()

plt.show()

The density plots show that with larger sample sizes, the spread of the sample means decreases, indicating less variability and a closer approximation to the normal distribution.

In [ ]:

The observed trend of decreasing standard deviation with increasing sample size supports the Central Limit Theorem. This demonstrates that for the SIR values of gastric surgeries, as the sample size increases, the distribution of sample means approximates a normal distribution, validating the CLT.

Hypothesis Testing on the dataset¶

Hypothesis 1:¶

  • Null Hypothesis: Hospitals with a bed capacity above 250 have a lower average SIR in comparison to smaller hospitals.

  • Alternative Hypothesis: Hospitals with a bed capacity above 250 have a higher average Standardized Infection Ratio (SIR) in comparison to smaller hospitals.

In [82]:
from scipy import stats

community_large_hospitals = df[(df['facility_type'] == 'Community, >250 Beds')]
community_small_hospitals = df[(df['facility_type'] == 'Community, <125 Beds') |
                                   (df['facility_type'] == 'Community, 125-250 Beds')]

mean_sir_community_large = community_large_hospitals['sir'].mean()
mean_sir_community_small = community_small_hospitals['sir'].mean()


t_stat_community, p_value_ttest_community = stats.ttest_ind(
    community_large_hospitals['sir'].dropna(),
    community_small_hospitals['sir'].dropna(),
    equal_var=False
)

Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Proportion of Mean SIR in Large vs. Small Hospitals')

Conclusion:¶

The t-test yields a P-value of 0.194, which is more than the traditional alpha requirement of 0.05.

Given these findings, the difference in the average Standardized Infection Ratio (SIR) between large and small hospitals is unlikely to be statistically significant.

As a result, it is not plausible to claim that larger hospitals have a lower average SIR when compared to smaller hospitals.

In practice, the findings of this study imply that the number of beds in a hospital has no significant effect on the Standardized Infection Ratio, as demonstrated in the studied data.

The negative t-statistic indicates that the mean reported infections are lower than the mean projected infections.

The discrepancy may arise due to several variables, such as the omission of developments in infection control techniques in the predictive models or the possibility of underreporting of illnesses.
